{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17622588","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17622588"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:03:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:03:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16804"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16804","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16804"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.45,0.41,0,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9495"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76914"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9495","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9495"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16804"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62419"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5165"},{"type":"tags","id":"10293"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22427"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22896"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76914","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76914"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old woman presents to the neurology clinic for management of generalised tonic-clonic seizures. She is prescribed valproate, which successfully controls her seizures. Her neurologist explains that this medication works by affecting specific neurotransmitter systems in the brain.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of valproate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increases acetylcholine release","Enhances GABA neurotransmission","Blocks glutamate receptors","Stimulates dopamine receptors","Blocks calcium channels exclusively"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary mechanism of action of valproate involves \u003Cstrong\u003Eenhancement of GABA neurotransmission\u003C/strong\u003E. This occurs through multiple mechanisms including increasing GABA synthesis, reducing GABA breakdown, and enhancing GABA receptor function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases acetylcholine release\u003C/strong\u003E - Valproate does not have significant effects on the cholinergic system and acetylcholine is not involved in its therapeutic action.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks glutamate receptors\u003C/strong\u003E - Although valproate may indirectly influence glutamate signalling, direct blockade of glutamate receptors is not its primary mechanism of action.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulates dopamine receptors\u003C/strong\u003E - Valproate does not interact directly with dopamine receptors and has no significant effects on dopaminergic neurotransmission.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks calcium channels exclusively\u003C/strong\u003E - While valproate may have some effects on calcium channels, this is not its sole or primary mechanism of action.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EValproate also blocks voltage-gated sodium channels, which contributes to its antiepileptic effects by reducing neuronal excitability. The combination of enhanced inhibitory (GABA) neurotransmission and reduced neuronal excitability makes it effective in treating seizures.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Valproate acts primarily by enhancing gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA) neurotransmission through multiple mechanisms.","Valproate inhibits voltage-gated sodium channels, reducing neuronal excitability.","Valproate increases GABA synthesis and reduces GABA breakdown, leading to increased inhibitory neurotransmission."],"references":[]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62419"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16804"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62419","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62419"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T20:25:34+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T20:25:54+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9495"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76914"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emed